Title : Peris Tobiko
Text : {{Orphan|date=February 2015}}

'''Peris Tobiko''' (born 1969) is a [[Kenya]]n politician.  She was elected the first female [[Maasai people|Maasai]] member of parliament in 2013 in a historic win even after elders had "cursed" her for defying the patriarchal norms of her community.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kenya Elects First Maasai Woman to Parliament|url=http://www.plaintalkbm.com/kenya-elects-first-maasai-woman-to-parliament/|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> She was re-elected for a second term as MP for [[Kajiado East Constituency]] in August 2017.<ref name=when/>

==Early life and education==
Tobiko was one of four daughters born to her mother, her father's first wife. She underwent [[female genital mutilation]] at age 10.<ref name=when/> Her [[illiterate]] father, whose [[polygamy|second wife]] bore him another ten children, tried to make her a [[child bride]] three times between the ages of 13 and 18. She ran away and had older women in the community report him to the police.<ref name=when>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-women-rulers-kenya/when-women-rule-kenyan-rebel-evades-child-marriage-and-maasai-curses-to-win-power-idUSKBN1CT00T|title=When Women Rule: Kenyan rebel evades child marriage and Maasai curses to win power|first=Katy|last=Migiro|publisher=Reuters|date=24 October 2017|accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref> Her mother faced being cast out of her home by her in-laws for failing to produce a male heir, as Tobiko later said, "girls are not considered to be children."<ref name=when/>

Tobiko studied political science at the [[University of Nairobi]].<ref name=when/>

==Career==
Tobiko worked for the government's pension fund, before running for parliament in 2007. She came third.<ref name=when/> When she won the party primaries in 2013, Maasai elders held a ceremony to curse her and those who voted for her.<ref name=when/> She was elected to represent Kajiado East, defeating her seven male rivals, making her the first female Maasai member of the [[National Assembly (Kenya)|National Assembly]]. She was re-elected in 2017, defeating another woman, Mary Seneta for the [[Jubilee Party]] nomination.<ref name=poise>{{cite web|url=https://www.nation.co.ke/news/politics/Power-women-of-Kajiado/1064-3954066-qk1l5y/index.html|title=Peris Tobiko: A portrait of power and poise|date=3 June 2017|accessdate=3 May 2019|work=Daily Nation|first=Joseph|last=Ngunjiri}}</ref>

Her priority has been education, focusing on building and upgrading schools and paying bursaries to keep girls in secondary education.<ref name=when/> She has said that she believes the [[Female education|education of girls]] "is the one single factor that can change society."<ref name=when/> She plans to run against incumbent [[Joseph Ole Lenku]] for governor of [[Kajiado County]] in 2022.<ref name=when/>

In January 2019, Tobiko was questioned by police and her colleague Henry Kimiti arrested after they were accused of inciting violence in an address to retrenched workers at the Kibini factory in Sultan Hamid.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001309949/kajiado-mca-arrested-arraigned-over-incitement|title=Kajiado MCA arrested, arraigned over incitement|work=Standard|date=19 January 2019|first=Peterson|last=Githaiga|accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref> She said she would "not be intimidated by anyone in her fight for peopleâ€™s rights."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-star.co.ke/counties/rift-valley/2019-01-23-mp-tobiko-quizzed-over-allegations-of-inciting-former-staff/|title=MP Tobiko quizzed over allegations of inciting former staff|first=Kurgat|last=Marindany|work=The Star|date=23 January 2019|accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref>

Tobiko is one of three women featured in the 2017 [[Thomson Reuters Foundation]] documentary ''When Women Rule'', alongside [[Kyrgyzstan]] MP [[Aida Kasymalieva]] and [[Bolivia]]n mayor [[Soledad Chapeton]].<ref name=time>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4991159/women-equality-in-government/|title=Meet the Women Who Are Breaking Glass Ceilings All Over the World in When Women Rule|work=Time|first=Tara|last=John|date=21 October 2017|accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref> She is also one of 200 renowned Kenyan women featured in the 2019 book, ''Pioneers & Transformers: The Journeys of Top Achieving Women in Kenya''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2001318170/book-on-top-women-achievers-to-be-launched|title=Book on top women achievers to be launched|first=Daniel|last=Psirmoi|work=Standard|date=26 March 2019|accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Tobiko married a banker from [[Narok]] she met at University.<ref name=poise/> They have two daughters, who were beaten up in their college car park after her 2013 victory by a group of young men who said, "Your mother should not come for our seat."<ref name=when/> Tobiko is a [[Christians|Christian]].<ref name=poise/> Tobiko has a 250-acre farm in Ikolosat village, where she raises cattle as well as herbs grown for export under her company "Maasai Flavours".<ref name=herbs>{{cite web|url=https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/business/article/2001275132/mp-i-keep-cattle-but-my-cash-cow-is-herbs|title=I keep cattle, but my cash cow is herbs: MP Tobiko|first=Caroline|last=Nyanga|work=Standard|date=31 March 2018|accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref>

